{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-12-20","name":"Patrick de Courcy","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Patrick de Courcy","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Patrick"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Courcy"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"–1251","fullLifespan":"–1251","birthPlace":{"address":"Cork, Ireland","geo":{"latitude":51.8983,"longitude":-8.4729,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1251","userCertifiedLifeSummary":"«b»Biography«/b»\nPatrick de Courcy; Baron Kinsale\n\nPatrick De Courcy, 2nd lord of Kingsale married Margery Fitz Stephen, daughter of Margaret de Cogan and granddaughter of Miles de Cogan; and through this marriage gained the Barony of Kingsale and Ringrone. Their son, Nicholas de Courcy became the third Lord Kingsale.\n\nPatrick de Courcy, Lord of Ringrone and Kinsale may have been an illegitimate son of John de Courcy.\n\nPatrick de Courcy, the second Baron, was joined in a commission, dated 17th July 1221 at Westminster, along with Thomas Fitz-Anthony, the Kings of Conaught, Leinster, and Munster, and divers of the nobility, were empowered to remove Sir Geoffrey de Marisco from the office of Lord Justiciar of Ireland and to substitute in his room Henry de Loundres, Archbishop of Dublin.\n\nHe died c. 1251-1253\n\nPatrick de Courcy ... He passed away about 1260.","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","place":"Cork, Ireland"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1208","date":"1208","place":"Ireland","id":"LCC6-X7L"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1212","date":"1212","place":"England","id":"GK12-8ZZ"},{"name":"Death of Spouse","sources":"0","year":"1221","date":"1221","id":"GK12-HKY"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","year":"1230","date":"ABT 1230","place":"Of,, Cork, Ireland","type":"Spousal","id":"2W7J-8TN"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1230","date":"1230","place":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","id":"L78X-PFZ