3","1167":"1167","1244":"1244","1221":"1221","1177":"1177","1208":"1208","Ireland":"Ierland","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland","Of,, Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"–1251":"–1251","1182–1244":"1182–1244","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1177–1221":"1177–1221","1212–1290":"1212–1290","1230–1290":"1230–1290","1160–1208":"1160–1208","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1182":"1182","1290":"1290","BEF 1261":"before 1261","1205":"1205","ABT 1230":"about 1230","1212":"1212","1223":"1223","1167":"1167","1244":"1244","1221":"1221","1177":"1177","1208":"1208","Ireland":"Ireland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Of,, Cork, Ireland":"County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Courcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":34,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Patrick de Courcy was born in Cork, County Cork, Ireland as the son of John Miles de Courcy. He married Margery FitzStephen about 1230, in County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1251."},"et":{"–1251":"–1251","1182–1244":"1182–1244","1185–1223":"1185–1223","1205–Female":"12